# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: proprotor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:proprotor/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] An **aerostat** (from Ancient Greek ἀήρ*(*aḗr*)* 'air' and στατός*(*statós*)* 'standing', via French) or **lighter-than-air aircraft** is an aircraft that relies on buoyancy to maintain flight.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Aerostats include unpowered balloons (free-flying or tethered) and powered airships.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] The relative density of an aerostat as a whole is lower than that of the surrounding atmospheric air (hence the name "lighter-than-air").
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Its main component is one or more gas capsules made of lightweight skins, containing a lifting gas (hot air, or any gas with lower density than air, typically hydrogen or helium) that displaces a large volume of air to generate enough buoyancy to overcome its own weight.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Payload (passengers and cargo) can then be carried on attached components such as a basket, a gondola, a cabin or various hardpoints.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] With airships, which need to be able to fly against wind, the lifting gas capsules are often protected by a more rigid outer envelope or an airframe, with other gasbags such as ballonets to help modulate buoyancy.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Aerostats are so named because they use aerostatic buoyant force that does not require any forward movement through the surrounding air mass, resulting in the inherent ability to levitate and perform vertical takeoff and landing.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] This contrasts with the heavier-than-air aerodynes that primarily use aerodynamic lift, which must have consistent airflow over an aerofoil (wing) surface to stay airborne.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] The term has also been used in a narrower sense, to refer to the statically tethered balloon in contrast to the free-flying airship.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] This article uses the term in its broader sense.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] In conventional usage, the term **aerostat** refers to any aircraft that remains aloft primarily using aerostatic buoyancy.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Historically, all aerostats were called balloons.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Powered types capable of horizontal flight were referred to as dirigible balloons or simply dirigibles (from the French *dirigeable*, meaning "steerable").
[src:proprotor/aerostat] These powered aerostats later came to be called airships, with the term "balloon" reserved for unpowered types, whether tethered (which means attached to the ground) or free-floating.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] More recently, the US Government Accountability Office has used the term "aerostat" in a different sense, to distinguish the statically tethered balloon from the free-flying airship.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] A balloon is an unpowered aerostat which has no means of propulsion and must be either tethered on a long cable or allowed to drift freely with the wind.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Although a free balloon travels at the speed of the wind, it is travelling with the wind so to a passenger the air feels calm and windless.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] To change its altitude it must either adjust the amount of lift or discard ballast weight.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Notable uses of free-flying balloons include meteorological balloons and sport balloons.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] A tethered balloon is held down by one or more mooring lines or tethers.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] It has sufficient lift to hold the line taut and its altitude is controlled by winching the line in or out.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] A round balloon is unstable and bobs about in strong winds, so the kite balloon was developed with an aerodynamic shape similar to a non-rigid airship.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Both kite balloons and non-rigid airships are sometimes called "blimps".
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Notable uses of tethered balloons include observation balloons and barrage balloons and notable uses of untethered balloons include espionage balloons and fire balloons.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] An airship is a powered, free-flying aerostat that can be steered.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Airships divide into rigid, semi-rigid and non-rigid types, with these last often known as blimps.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] A rigid airship has an outer framework or skin surrounding the lifting gas bags inside it, the outer envelope keeps its shape even if the gasbags are deflated.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] The great zeppelin airships of the twentieth century were rigid types.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] A non-rigid airship or blimp deflates like a balloon as it loses gas.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] The Goodyear blimps are still a common sight in the USA.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] A semi-rigid airship has a deflatable gas bag like a non-rigid but with a supporting structure to help it hold its shape while aloft.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] The first practical airship, the Santos-Dumont No.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Some airships obtain additional lift aerodynamically as they travel through the air, using the shape of their envelope or through the addition of fins or even small wings.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Types designed to exploit this lifting effect in normal cruise are called hybrid airships.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] A hybrid type uses both static buoyancy and dynamic airflow to provide lift.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] The dynamic movement may be created either using propulsive power as a hybrid airship or by tethering in the wind like a kite, as a Helikite or kytoon.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Helikites do not need ballonets and so are simpler in construction than traditional aerostats and Helikites do not need constant electrical power to keep them airborne.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Helikites are also extremely stable and so are good aerial platforms for cameras or scientific instruments.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Helikites are one of the most popular aerostat designs and are widely used by the scientific community, military, photographers, geographers, police, first responders.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Helikites range in size from 1 metre (gas volume 0.13 m3) with a pure helium lift of 30g, up to 14 metres (gas volume 250m3) able to lift 117 kg.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Small Helikites can fly up to altitudes of 1,000 ft, and medium-sized Helikites up to altitudes of 3,000 ft, while large Helikites can achieve 7,000 ft.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] The Allsopp Helikite is a combination of a helium balloon and a kite to form a single, aerodynamically sound tethered aircraft, that exploits both wind and helium for its lift.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Helikites are considered the most stable, energy and cost-efficient aerostats available.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Piasecki Helicopter developed the Piasecki PA-97 Helistat using the rotor systems from four obsolete helicopters and a surplus Navy blimp, in order to provide a capability to lift heavier loads than a single helicopter could provide.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] The aircraft suffered a fatal accident during a test flight.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] In 2008, Boeing and SkyHook International resurrected the concept and announced a proposed design of the SkyHook JHL-40.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] In order to provide buoyancy, any lifting gas must be less dense than the surrounding air.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] A hot air balloon is open at the bottom to allow hot air to enter, while the gas balloon is closed to stop the (cold) lifting gas from escaping.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Common lifting gases have included hydrogen, coal gas and helium.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] This lowers its density and creates lift.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Small hot air balloons or lanterns have been flown in China since ancient times.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] The first modern man-lifting aerostat, made by the Montgolfier brothers, was a hot air balloon.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Most early balloons however were gas balloons.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Interest in the sport of hot air ballooning reawoke in the second half of the twentieth century and even some hot-air airships have been flown.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Hydrogen is the lightest of all gases and a manned hydrogen balloon was flown soon after the Montgolfier brothers.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] There is no need to burn fuel, so a gas balloon can stay aloft far longer than a hot-air balloon.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Hydrogen soon became the most common lifting gas for both balloons and, later, airships.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] But hydrogen itself is flammable and, following several major disasters in the 1930s, including the Hindenburg Disaster, it fell out of use.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Coal gas comprises a mix of methane and other gases, and typically has about half the lifting power of hydrogen.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] In the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries municipal gas works became common and provided a cheap source of lifting gas.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Some works were able to produce a special mix for ballooning events, incorporating a higher proportion of hydrogen and less carbon monoxide, to improve its lifting power.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Helium is the only lifting gas which is both non-flammable and non-toxic, and it has almost as much (about 92%) lifting power as hydrogen.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] It was not discovered in quantity until early in the twentieth century, and for many years only the United States had enough to use in airships.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Almost all gas balloons and airships now use helium.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Although not currently practical, it may be possible to construct a rigid, lighter-than-air structure which, rather than being inflated with air, is at a vacuum relative to the surrounding air.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] This would allow the object to float above the ground without any heat or special lifting gas, but the structural challenges of building a rigid vacuum chamber lighter than air are quite significant.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Even so, it may be possible to improve the performance of more conventional aerostats by trading gas weight for structural weight, combining the lifting properties of the gas with vacuum and possibly heat for enhanced lift.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] The buoyancy control of an aerostat relies on the principles of buoyant force and the manipulation of the gas inside its envelope.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Aerostats use lighter-than-air gases, such as helium or hydrogen, which provide lift because they are less dense than the surrounding air.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] The amount of buoyant force generated depends on the volume of the gas, its density, and the density of the outside atmosphere.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] By controlling these variables, an aerostat can be made to rise, descend, or maintain a stable altitude.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] The basic mechanism involves adjusting the volume and pressure of the gas within the aerostat’s envelope, often through a system of valves and compartments.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] To ascend, the aerostat releases ballast, which typically consists of sandbags or other weights, reducing its overall weight and making it lighter than the air it displaces.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Alternatively, it may adjust the temperature of the gas (if using hot air) or expand the volume of gas within its envelope.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] As the gas volume increases, the aerostat becomes less dense and rises.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] This is controlled either through heating (in the case of hot air balloons) or by adjusting the valves that manage the flow of gas between different compartments or the outside atmosphere.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Helium-based aerostats, such as blimps, rely on maintaining the integrity and volume of the helium within their envelope to achieve a stable lift.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] When descending, the aerostat must reduce its buoyancy, which can be done by venting some of the gas or by taking on additional ballast.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Venting gas allows the envelope to lose volume, making the aerostat denser than the surrounding air and causing it to descend.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] However, venting must be done cautiously, especially with helium, as it is a limited resource and cannot be replenished easily during flight.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Alternatively, an aerostat might use a reversible system where it can compress the gas into smaller compartments within the envelope, reducing lift without permanently losing the gas.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] By managing these compartments or adjusting the flow of gas, the aerostat’s buoyancy can be precisely controlled.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] To maintain altitude, an aerostat achieves a balance where the lift force generated by the gas equals the weight of the aerostat.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] This equilibrium is achieved through small adjustments in ballast or the gas volume.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] Sophisticated systems might use automatic valves and sensors to monitor atmospheric pressure, gas volume, and temperature, ensuring that the aerostat remains stable without manual intervention.
[src:proprotor/aerostat] This constant regulation allows aerostats to hover at a fixed altitude for extended periods, making them useful for applications such as surveillance, communication relays, or scientific observations, where maintaining a consistent position in the atmosphere is crucial.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:proprotor/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:proprotor/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:proprotor/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:proprotor/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The **Leonardo AW609**, formerly the **AgustaWestland AW609**, and originally the **Bell-Agusta BA609**, is a twin-engined tiltrotor VTOL aircraft with an overall configuration similar to that of the Bell Boeing V-22 Osprey.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] It is capable of landing vertically like a helicopter while having a range and speed in excess of conventional rotorcraft.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The AW609 is aimed at the civil aviation market, in particular VIP customers and offshore oil and gas operators.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] It has progressed from a concept in the late 1990s, to development and testing, and is working towards certification in the 2020s.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The BA609 drew on experience gained from Bell's earlier experimental tiltrotor, the XV-15.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 1996, Bell and Boeing formed a partnership to develop a civil tiltrotor aircraft.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In March 1998, Boeing pulled out of the project.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In September 1998, Agusta became a partner in the development program.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The Italian government subsidized Agusta's development of a military tiltrotor, and as the AW609 has civilian aspects, the European Commission requires AgustaWestland to pay back progressive amounts per aircraft to the Italian state to avoid a distortion of competition.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] As of 2015, Bell continues to perform contract work on the AW609 program, while considering commercial potential for the bigger V-280 tiltrotor, where military production may reach larger numbers and hence reduce unit cost.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2016, Bell preferred the 609 for commercial applications and kept the V-280 for military use only.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Bell stated that conventional helicopters were not part of Bell's future for military customers.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The aircraft's purpose is to take off and land vertically, but fly faster than a helicopter.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Over 45 different aircraft have flown proving VTOL and STOL capabilities, of which the V-22, Harrier "jump jet" family, Yakovlev Yak-38 and Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II jets have proceeded to production.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] By 2008, Bell had estimated that very light jets and large offshore helicopters like the Sikorsky S-92 had reduced the potential market for tiltrotors.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Also in 2008, it was reported that limited funding of the program by both Bell and AgustaWestland had resulted in slow flight testing progress.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In September 2009, AgustaWestland chief executive Giuseppe Orsi said that corporate parent Finmeccanica had authorised buying Bell Helicopter out of the program to speed it up, as Bell was dissatisfied with the commercial prospects and wanted to spend the resources on other programs.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2013 AgustaWestland estimated a market of 700 aircraft over 20 years.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] By 2011, negotiations centred on the full transfer of technologies shared with the V-22, however Bell stated that no technology was shared with the V-22.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] At the 2011 Paris Air Show, AgustaWestland stated that it will assume full ownership of the programme, redesignating the aircraft as "AW609", and that Bell Helicopter will remain in the role of component design and certification.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In November 2011, the exchange of ownership was completed, following the granting of regulatory approval; media estimated that the transfer happened at little cost.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] On 6 December 2002, the first ground tests of the BA609 prototype began.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The first flight took place on 7 March 2003 in Arlington, Texas, flown by test pilots Roy Hopkins and Dwayne Williams.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] After 14 hours of helicopter-mode flight testing, the prototype was moved to a ground testing rig to study the operational effects of the conversion modes.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Following the completion of ground-based testing, on 3 June 2005 the prototype resumed flight testing, focusing on the expansion of its flight envelope.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] On 22 July 2005, the first conversion from helicopter to aeroplane mode while in flight took place.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] By October 2008, 365 flight-hours had been logged by two prototype aircraft.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The AW609 demonstrated a safe dual-engine failure in normal cruise flight on 15 May 2009.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] By February 2012, this had risen to 650 hours, and it was reported that 85 per cent of the AW609's flight envelope had been explored.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Test pilot Paul Edwards has stated that the AW609 was not susceptible to the vortex ring state phenomena, naturally slipping out of the vortex on its own since both rotors will not simultaneously enter the vortex ring state.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2011, AgustaWestland began construction of a third prototype.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] That prototype was still not fully assembled by February 2015.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The company plans to conduct test flights in Italy in the summer of 2015.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] AgustaWestland planned to then disassemble it and ship it to Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, to prepare it for tests of the de-icing system in Minnesota.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] A fourth prototype, to be used in the development and testing of new avionics and control systems, was also underway.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] By November 2012, over 700 flight hours had been accumulated by the two operational prototypes.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In January 2014, it was reported that in excess of 850 flying hours had been accumulated by the two prototypes.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Accumulated flight data is used to further develop representative simulators, which are in turn being used to support the development program.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] By March 2015, the two prototype aircraft had accumulated 1,200 hours, of about 2,000 hours necessary for certification.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Two more aircraft were expected to fly that year.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2015, AgustaWestland reported that the AW609 flew 721 miles (1,161 km) from Yeovil, UK, to Milan, Italy, in 2 hours 18 minutes.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In September 2015, the first AW609 prototype was reportedly nearing the end of its service life, while a third prototype was finishing construction at the company's Vergiate facility and a fourth prototype was being built in Philadelphia.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] On 30 October 2015, the second of the two prototypes (N609AG) crashed near AgustaWestland's Vergiate facility in north west Italy, killing both pilots.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2002, Type certification of the aircraft was projected for 2007.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2007, certification was projected for 2011.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In August 2012, the aircraft was forecast to receive Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) and European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) certification in early 2016.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The company expected to achieve FAA certification in 2017.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Some delays were caused by lack of funding for the FAA, others by the V-22 troubles, while AgustaWestland also spent time increasing performance and reducing cost.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2012, the FAA stated that the AW609 was to be certified in compliance with both helicopter and fixed-wing aircraft rules.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] New codes were to be developed to cover the transition phase between the two modes.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Of the 217 Pilot Training Tasks, 10 are unique tiltrotor tasks.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] AW609 Certification Basis is established by the FAA under the provisions of Part 21.17(b) for "Special Class Aircraft" along with a portion of Part 25 (fixed-wing aircraft) and 29 (helicopter) and new specific tiltrotor parts in a new category called "powered lift".
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In January 2013, the FAA defined US tiltrotor noise rules to comply with ICAO rules, expecting the AW609 to be available within 10 years.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Noise certification will cost $588,000, which is the same as for a large helicopter.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In February 2014, the AW609 conducted its first customer demonstration flights, in both airplane and helicopter modes, and began certification flights.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In early summer 2014, the AW609 performed FAA-monitored autorotation tests.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] More than 79 power-off conversions from airplane mode to helicopter mode were made across 10 flight hours.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] During these tests, it was found that the minimum operating requirements for successful autorotation include the altitude being 3,000 ft (910 m), and that the system keeps rotor rpm above the minimum 70% for stable recovery.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Kincheloe Award for their role in the tests.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In February 2023, pilots from the US Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) flew the AW609 tiltrotor, representing the first time the regulator's pilots had flown the type.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The Leonardo company described the flight as a pre-TIA (type inspection authorization) activity, as it moves towards the final stage of the certification process.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] EASA pilots subsequently commenced familarisation flights in March 2023 with certification and entry into service projected to be sometime in 2024.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] At the Farnborough Air Show in July 2012, AgustaWestland announced a higher-weight variant of the AW609, up to 17,500 pounds or 7,900 kilograms.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] This model would trade some of its vertical takeoff performance for increased payload capacity.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Officials from AgustaWestland have suggested that this short take off and vertical landing (STOVL) variant may be an attractive option for search and rescue and maritime operators.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] According to senior vice-president of marketing Roberto Garavaglia, the Italian government is interested in acquiring several AW609s for coastal patrol duties.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Due to an agreement with Bell, these may not feature armament.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In June 2013, AgustaWestland announced that work to integrate design changes as part of a major modernisation would delay the AW609's certification by up to one year.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] These design changes primarily involved aerodynamic improvements, aimed at achieving a 10% reduction in drag and a significant reduction in overall weight, increasing the AW609's performance and capabilities.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Separate improvement programs were underway on the aircraft's engines and avionics systems.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2015, AgustaWestland announced the development of external fuel tanks which would permit 800 nmi (920 mi; 1,500 km) flights carrying six passengers over three hours.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2013, AgustaWestland was considering a US-based final assembly point for production AW609s.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Managing director Robert LaBelle stated that 35% of the customers for the tiltrotor are expected to come from the US market.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Reportedly, the primary production line was to be located in Italy while a second production line in the US was under consideration.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2015 AgustaWestland announced that the AW609 will be produced at its Philadelphia facility, the production site for the AW139, AW119 KXe and AW169.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Two to three AW609 aircraft will be assembled there beginning in 2017, and once production matures, a second final assembly line is being considered for Italy.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Leonardo has a flight simulator in Philadelphia to assist pilot training in the peculiarities of flying a tiltrotor.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2015, Bristow Helicopters and AgustaWestland agreed to develop dedicated offshore oil and gas transport, and search and rescue configurations for the AW609.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In March 2015, Bristow Group signed a joint development agreement with AgustaWestland at Heli-Expo, which would allow Bristow to exclusively direct the direction of the tiltrotor for offshore missions such as oil and gas operations.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The changes could extend beyond the AW609 to potentially affect the design of larger and more advanced models that AgustaWestland was planning to introduce in the early 2020s.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The introduction of tiltrotors would allow for point-to-point operations, flying oil company personnel to platforms from major population centers with a greater margin of safety.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Industry journalists viewed the agreement as an approval of the tiltrotor technology from the commercial industry, where previously only the military were interested.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In the early 2020s there was interest in a military version; an AW609 for utility, medevac, or search and rescue versions began to be discussed more seriously.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The AW609 is a tiltrotor aircraft capable of performing vertical landings whereas conventional fixed-wing aircraft cannot, allowing the type to serve locations such as heliports or very small airports, while possessing twice the speed and the range of any available helicopter.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] AgustaWestland promotes the type as "...combining the benefits of a helicopter and a fixed-wing aircraft into one aircraft".
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The AW609 appears to be outwardly similar to the military-orientated V-22 Osprey.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] However, the two aircraft share few components.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Unlike the V-22, the AW609 has a pressurised cabin.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] As of 2013, multiple cabin configurations have been projected, including a standard nine-passenger layout, a six-to-seven-passenger VIP/executive cabin, and a search and rescue model featuring a hoist/basket and four single seats.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Medevac and patrol/surveillance-orientated variants have been proposed.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] For increased passenger comfort, the cabin is pressurised and equipped with soundproofing.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Access to the cabin is via a 35-inch-wide (89 cm), two-piece clamshell door, center-set into the fuselage underneath the wings.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The AW609 is powered by a pair of Pratt & Whitney Canada PT6C-67A turboshaft engines, which each drive a three-bladed proprotor.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] These engines possess roughly twice the horsepower of the similarly sized AgustaWestland AW169 helicopter.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Both of the engine and proprotor pairs are mounted on a load-bearing rotatable pylon at the wing's ends, allowing the proprotors to be positioned at various angles.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In helicopter mode, the proprotors can be positioned between a 75- and 95-degree angle from the horizontal, with 87 degrees being the typical selection for hovering vertically.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In airplane mode, the proprotors are rotated forward and locked in position at a zero-degree angle, spinning at 84% RPM.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The flight control software reportedly handles much of the complexity of the transitioning between helicopter and airplane modes.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Automated systems guide pilots to the correct tilt angle and air speed settings.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] When flying in airplane mode, the majority of lift is produced by the AW609's wings, which are slightly forward-swept.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Both the wing and the main fuselage are made largely of composite materials.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The 34-foot-long (10 m) wings feature flaperon control surfaces which are normally automatically controlled.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In vertical flight, the flaperons drop to a 66-degree downwards angle to reduce the wing area being encountered by downwash from the proprotors.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] A high-mounted rudderless vertical stabiliser is attached the rear of the fuselage to stabilise flight while in aircraft mode.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In the event of a single engine failure, either engine can provide power to both proprotors via a drive shaft.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The AW609 is also capable of autorotation.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The AW609 has been designed to achieve Full Transport Category/Class 1 performance, to operate safely even when flown under single engine conditions.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] It is equipped with a de-icing system, and is to be certified for flying into known icing conditions.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Building on experiences with the V-22, the AW609 is outfitted with a sink rate warning system.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Avionics include a triple-redundant digital fly-by-wire flight control system, a head-up display system, and Full Authority Digital Engine Controls (FADEC).
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The cockpit has been designed so that the AW609 can be flown by a single pilot in instrument flight rules conditions.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Several of the aircraft's controls, such as blade pitch, are designed to resemble and function their counterparts on conventional rotorcraft, enabling helicopter pilots to transition to the type more easily.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Elements of the aircraft's controls feature touchscreen interfaces.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Shortly following AgustaWestland's full acquisition of the program, a substantial modernisation of the AW609's design was initiated in 2012.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] These changes included new engines and the redesigning of the cockpit.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] As part of the design refresh, new flight management systems, Northrop Grumman inertial and GPS navigation systems, and other avionics from Rockwell Collins were adopted.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Bell/Agusta aimed the aircraft "at the government and military markets".
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Another key market for the AW609 has been offshore oil and gas operations, which require aircraft capable of traversing the increasing distances involved.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2001, Bell estimated a market for 1,000 aircraft.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Bell/Agusta stated in 2007 that they intend for the BA609 to compete with corporate business jets and helicopters, and that the BA609 would be of interest to any operator that has a mixed fleet of fixed wing and rotary wing aircraft.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Michael Hough, USMC deputy commandant for aviation, requested that Bell conduct studies into arming the BA609, potentially to act as an escort for V-22s.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] However, AgustaWestland's deal with Bell for taking over the BA609 program precludes the aircraft from carrying arms.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2001, Terry Stinson, then chairman and CEO of Bell Helicopters, declared that the aircraft will cost "at least US$10 million".
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2004, Don Barbour, then executive marketing director, stated that "early orders had been taken at a price of between $8 and $10 million." Since 1999, orders have been at a price to be confirmed no later than 24 months before aircraft delivery.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2012, industry reporters estimated that the final price tag may come to $30 million per unit.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2015, some believed the price to be only around $24 million.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 1999, there were 77 confirmed orders.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2012, there were 70 orders, depending on the final unit price.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] As of March 2015, there were 60 orders for the AW609.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The company intends to have production facilities ready for completing orders right after FAA certification.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Bristow Helicopters intends to order 10 or more.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Michael Bloomberg, the U.S. billionaire businessman and politician, is "near the top" of the list of buyers who have put a deposit down on the AW609 tiltrotor aircraft.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In February 2015, the Italian Army released a white paper documenting its vision of future procurement efforts.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] It included the intention to procure a force of tiltrotor aircraft for rapid troop-transport and medical evacuation duties.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] It has been speculated in the media that the AW609 is a likely candidate for the requirement.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In November 2015, United Arab Emirates selected a search and rescue variant of the AW609, signing a memorandum of understanding for three, with an option for three more.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] As of May 2019, no contract with the UAE has been signed.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] While AW609s were being built at AWPC Philadelphia in March 2022, Leonardo projected entry into service in 2023.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In 2023, the AW609 entered the final stage of flight certification, and as of 2024 it was estimated this process could be completed in 2025.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] In March 2026, Leonardo stated that it expected the AW609 to enter commercial service in 2027.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] On 30 October 2015, the second of the two prototypes (N609AG), which first flew in 2006, crashed near AgustaWestland's Vergiate facility in North West Italy, killing long-time test pilots Pietro Venanzi and Herb Moran.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The aircraft broke up in midair after 27 minutes of flight, on a flight plan that included high speed testing.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] Investigators consider the most likely cause to be changes in flight control laws and tail changes.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] These led to a "Dutch roll" instability while diving at 293 kn (337 mph; 542 km/h) where previously only 285 kn (328 mph; 528 km/h) had been achieved.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The Italian authorities seized the third prototype in May 2016, and returned it for flight testing in July.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The final report stated that during a high-speed dive with a left turn, "slight lateral-direction oscillations" started on roll-out and grew in amplitude and frequency.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] The pilot attempted to correct the roll with "counterphase input roll manoeuvres and then pedal inputs", but this did not dampen the oscillations.
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] They instead became divergent, bringing the sideslip angle at 10.5°, well above the 4° maximum allowed, "inducing contact of the right proprotor with the right wing due to excessive flapping of the proprotor blades".
[src:proprotor/agustawestland-aw609] This severed fuel and hydraulic lines in the wing leading edge, triggering a fire.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] An **air-start system** is a power source used to provide the initial rotation to start large diesel engines and gas turbines.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Compared to a gasoline (petrol) engine, a diesel engine has a very high compression ratio, an essential design feature, as it is the heat of compression that ignites the fuel.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] An electric starter with sufficient power to turn a large diesel engine would itself be so large as to be impractical so there is a need for an alternative system.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] An air start system has three main components along with various safety components, namely the air start injector, the distributor and the air receivers.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] When the system is initiated, starting air from the receivers is distributed by the distributor unit to each respective air start valve according to the firing order of the engine’s cylinders.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Safety components include flame traps, to prevent air line explosions, a turning gear interlock which ensures that air-start cannot be initiated when the turning gear is engaged, relief valves and isolation valves, as well as drain valves at certain points along the system.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Control components include the control valves and remote air-start valves.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] A direct start system as used on a marine slow-speed diesel is required to have up to 12 starts on a non-reversing engine or 6 starts on a reversible, or geared, engine.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] When starting the engine, compressed air is admitted to whichever cylinder has a piston just over top dead center, forcing it downward.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] As the engine starts to turn, the air-start valve on the next cylinder in line opens to continue the rotation.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] After several rotations, fuel is injected into the cylinders, the engine starts running and the air is cut off.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] To further complicate matters, a large engine is usually "blown over" first with zero fuel settings and the indicator cocks open, to prove that the engine is clear of any water build up and that everything is free to turn.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] After a successful blow ahead and a blow astern, the indicator cocks are closed on all the cylinders, and then the engine can be started on fuel.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Significant complexity is added to the engine by using an air-start system, as the cylinder head must have an extra valve in each cylinder to admit the air in for starting, plus the required control systems.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] This added complexity and cost limits the use of air-starters to very large and expensive reciprocating engines.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Another method of air-starting an internal combustion engine is by using compressed air or gas to drive a fluid motor in place of an electric motor.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] They can be used to start engines from 5 to 320 liters in size and if more starting power is necessary two or more motors can be used.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Starters of this type are used in place of electric motors because of their lighter weight and higher reliability.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] They can also outlast an electric starter by a factor of three and are easier to rebuild.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Engines operating in underground mining activities tend to operate on this type of starter system to reduce the risk of an electrical system igniting flammable material.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] All vane type air starters should have a lubricator installed to insure long-life and maximum performance.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Lubricators give the moving parts a needed friction barrier, reduce metal corrosion and keep vanes sealed properly against the cylinder walls.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Even the so-called lube-free air starters require lubrication to prolong trouble free life.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Two basic lubricator devices are typically employed.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] One is an in-line or reservoir type that typically stores up to 2 quarts of lubricant, and is installed along the air supply line.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] The second style of lubricator is a small one shot device that dispenses a measured amount of lubricant every time the starter is engaged.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Installed directly onto the air inlet of the starter, the in-line lubricators are self priming pneumatic pumps that require a 1/4″ lubrication line piped from as far away as 4 feet.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Air Starter lubricators perform best using misting type, non-detergent oils such as diesel fuel or Marvel Mystery oil.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] If emissions are a concern, there are environmentally friendly type lubricants available on the market.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Not all air starters require lubrication.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Turbine type air starters do not require air motor lubrication, although some turbine air starters do use an oil filled transmission that may require periodic inspections and maintenance.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Compressed air has been used to start gas turbine engines using air impingement starting (in which air is directed at the engine turbine blades through nozzles in the turbine casing, used on US Navy General Electric J79 engines).
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] It is much more efficient to use an air turbine starter (ATS) which is usually mounted on an accessory gearbox.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] An early axial compressor turbojet had an ATS located in the compressor nose cone (eg particular variants of the J79).
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Air impingement starting was not used for US military aircraft after the F-4B, A-5A and F-5 as the pneumatic energy requirement was several times greater than when using an air turbine starter.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] The gas turbine compressor required to start a J79 with impingement starting was sufficient to start two J79 engines simultaneously in a B-58 when using air turbine starters.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] An ATS has its own turbine and gears to change its low torque and high speed to low speed and high torque at the engine mounting pad.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Further gears in the engine gearbox connect to the engine shaft (high pressure spool on multi-spool engines).
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] Compared with electric starters, air-starters have a higher power-to-weight ratio so are used on large engines as an electric starter would be too big and, with its cables, too heavy and expensive.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] However, for smaller engines, which don't need as much starter power, an electric starter is more suitable.
[src:proprotor/air-start-system] It has a dual function as a generator (is known as a starter/generator) at speeds above which the engine no longer requires starter assistance.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:proprotor/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] A **proprotor** is a spinning airfoil that functions as both an airplane-style propeller and a helicopter-style rotor.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] Several proprotor-equipped convertiplanes, such as the Bell Boeing V-22 Osprey tiltrotor, are capable of switching back and forth between flying akin to both helicopters and fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] Accordingly this type of airfoil has been predominantly applied to vertical takeoff and landing (VTOL) aircraft.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] On several aerial vehicles such as the AgustaWestland AW609 and V-22 Osprey, a pair of three-bladed proprotors have been used.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] Both the proprotors and engines are mounted on load-bearing rotatable pylon at the wingtips, allowing the proprotors to be positioned at various angles.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] STOL rolling-takeoff and landing capability is achieved by having the nacelles tilted forward up to 45°.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] Typically, flight control software would perform much of the complex transition between the distinct helicopter and aeroplane modes; while automated systems are usually provided to inform crews on the optimal tilt angle and air speed to pursue.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] Furthermore, it is typical for flight controls, such as blade pitch, to both resemble and function akin to their counterparts on conventional rotorcraft, easing the transition of conventional helicopter pilots to such vehicles.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] Proprotors can be designed to fold for storage purposes.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] However, in the case of the V-22, in order to facilitate proprotor folding, the proprotor's diameter had to be constrained to a diameter of 38-foot (11.6 m), five feet (1.5 m) less than optimal for vertical takeoff; this difference has been attributed for causing relatively high disk loading.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] In a typical implementation, both proprotors must be rotating in order to maintain flight in helicopter mode.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] To guard against instances of single engine failure, on both the V-22 and AW609, both engines are connected by drive shafts to a common central gearbox so that one engine can power both proprotors if such a failure occurs.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] Despite this provision, the V-22 is generally not capable of hovering on a single engine.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] If a proprotor gearbox fails, that proprotor cannot be feathered, and both engines must be stopped prior to an emergency landing.
[src:proprotor/proprotor] The autorotation characteristics are poor partly due to the rotors' low inertia.
